Dear Tamar,

I hope that you are well.  Please see the standard email we are sending c=
lients about the HMRC's requirement to correct regime.  Please let me kno=
w if you have any questions.



Dear Client,

HMRC "Requirement to Correct" Regime

Background

We are writing in relation to HM Revenue & Customs' (HMRC) 'Requirement t=
o Correct' (RTC) regime which comes to an end on 30th September 2018.

Many of you will have already discussed this with your Tax Advisers and/o=
r may have recently received a standard letter from HMRC regarding the re=
gime.  In summary, it relates to historic tax non-compliance with an offs=
hore connection.  Non-compliance that must be rectified under the RTC inc=
ludes a failure to notify HMRC of chargeability to tax, failure to file a=
 return or other specified document or submitting to HMRC a return or oth=
er relevant document containing an inaccuracy.

Broadly speaking where offshore non-compliance has taken place an intenti=
on to make a disclosure to correct the offshore non-compliance from befor=
e 6 April 2017 must be registered with HMRC by 30th September 2018. If an=
 intention to make a disclosure to correct offshore non-compliance is not=
 registered by 30th September 2018, with the disclosure being made within=
 the following 90 days, taxpayers could ultimately be liable to a Failure=
 to Correct (FTC) penalty of 200% of the tax if there is no 'reasonable e=
xcuse' for the failure to correct.

The requirement covers Income Tax and Capital Gains Tax which HMRC could =
have assessed at 5th April 2017 and Inheritance Tax assessable at 17th No=
vember 2017 thus potentially covering the years back to 1997 in some case=
s.

Relevance to individuals who are UK resident but non-UK domiciled

The RTC is potentially particularly relevant to UK resident, non-UK domic=
iled individuals due to the international nature of their affairs and the=
 additional complexities of claiming the remittance basis of taxation.

We have therefore been undertaking a general review of accounts held by o=
ur UK resident but non-UK domiciled customers to gauge any possible relev=
ance of RTC to them.  At this stage our overall observation is that, with=
 the exception of transfers to the UK in order to pay the remittance basi=
s charge, which should benefit from a specific remittance exemption, very=
 few customers remit funds other than 'clean capital' to the UK.  Given t=
hat such transfers do not normally need to be reported to HMRC we would n=
ot therefore generally expect that there should be RTC issues to consider=
 (assuming the remittance basis has been appropriately claimed each year =
and, where relevant, the remittance basis charge has been paid).

However, given the broad scope of RTC and the fact that the visibility we=
 have of our Clients' financial affairs is limited to the accounts held a=
t HSBC Private Banking (C.I.) we are taking this opportunity to write to =
all individuals who we believe may be claiming, or have claimed in the pa=
st, the remittance basis of taxation in the UK.

Should you have any questions about reporting under the RTC, please discu=
ss this with your Tax Adviser as HSBC does not provide tax advice. Your R=
elationship Manager will be pleased to assist with any information that m=
ay be required with a disclosure.

Yours faithfully,

HSBC Private Bank



Kind regards,
Tilly

